# Jarvis API and Credentials Setup Guide

You do not need every API below.
Jarvis is local-first, so you can run it with Ollama only and then add cloud providers or integrations one by one.

## Step 1: Open the right files

Jarvis loads secrets from `.env` when it starts.

Use these files as your reference:

- `.env.example`
- `config/settings.env.template`

If `.env` already exists, edit it.
If it does not exist, create it based on those two template files.

## Step 2: Set the minimum things first

### 2.1 Create your dashboard token

This is not from any website. You make it yourself.

Add this to `.env`:

```env
JARVIS_DASHBOARD_TOKEN=replace_with_a_long_random_secret
```

### 2.2 Choose how Jarvis will run its LLM

Option A: Local-first with Ollama

1. Install Ollama from `https://ollama.com/`
2. Start Ollama:

```powershell
ollama serve
```

3. Pull at least one model:

```powershell
ollama pull deepseek-r1:8b
```

Optional models mentioned by the repo:

```powershell
ollama pull mistral:7b
ollama pull llava
```

Option B: Cloud fallback

Add at least one cloud key. Recommended first key:

- `GEMINI_API_KEY`

Optional extra providers:

- `GROQ_API_KEY`
- `OPENAI_API_KEY`
- `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`

## Step 3: Get each API or credential

Only do the sections for the features you want to use.

### 3.1 Gemini

Use this if you want the main cloud fallback.

1. Go to `https://aistudio.google.com/`
2. Sign in with your Google account
3. Create an API key
4. Put it in `.env`

```env
GEMINI_API_KEY=your_key_here
```

### 3.2 OpenAI

Use this only if you want OpenAI as an optional fallback provider.

1. Go to `https://platform.openai.com/`
2. Open the API keys section
3. Create a new secret key
4. Put it in `.env`

```env
OPENAI_API_KEY=your_key_here
```

### 3.3 Groq

1. Go to `https://console.groq.com/`
2. Create an API key
3. Put it in `.env`

```env
GROQ_API_KEY=your_key_here
```

### 3.4 Anthropic

1. Go to `https://console.anthropic.com/`
2. Create an API key
3. Put it in `.env`

```env
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=your_key_here
```

### 3.5 Telegram

Needed for Telegram messaging integration.

1. Open Telegram
2. Search for `@BotFather`
3. Run `/newbot`
4. Follow the prompts and copy the bot token
5. Send at least one message to your bot
6. Open this URL in your browser, replacing `<TOKEN>` with your real bot token:

```text
https://api.telegram.org/bot<TOKEN>/getUpdates
```

7. Find the `chat.id` value in the response
8. Put both values in `.env`

```env
TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=your_bot_token_here
TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID=your_chat_id_here
```

### 3.6 Google Calendar and Gmail

Needed for both the Calendar and Gmail integrations.

You need:

- `GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID`
- `GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET`
- `GOOGLE_REFRESH_TOKEN`

Steps:

1. Go to `https://console.cloud.google.com/`
2. Create or select a Google Cloud project
3. Enable these APIs:
   Calendar API
   Gmail API
4. Configure the OAuth consent screen
5. Create OAuth client credentials
6. Copy the Client ID and Client Secret
7. Use OAuth Playground to generate a refresh token:
   `https://developers.google.com/oauthplayground/`
8. In OAuth Playground settings, enable "Use your own OAuth credentials"
9. Paste your Google Client ID and Client Secret there
10. Request these scopes:
    `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar.events`
    `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.readonly`
    `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.send`
    `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/gmail.modify`
11. Authorize access
12. Exchange the authorization code for tokens
13. Copy the refresh token
14. Put all three values in `.env`

```env
GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=your_client_id_here
GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=your_client_secret_here
GOOGLE_REFRESH_TOKEN=your_refresh_token_here
```

### 3.7 Notion

1. Go to `https://www.notion.so/my-integrations`
2. Create a new internal integration
3. Copy the integration secret
4. Share the pages or databases you want Jarvis to access with that integration
5. Put the secret in `.env`

```env
NOTION_API_KEY=your_notion_secret_here
```

### 3.8 Spotify

Needed for playback, search, and playlist tools.

You need:

- `SPOTIFY_CLIENT_ID`
- `SPOTIFY_CLIENT_SECRET`
- `SPOTIFY_REFRESH_TOKEN`

Steps:

1. Go to `https://developer.spotify.com/dashboard`
2. Create an app
3. Copy the Client ID and Client Secret
4. Add a redirect URI such as:

```text
http://localhost:8888/callback
```

5. Run the Spotify Authorization Code flow to get a refresh token
6. Approve these scopes if requested:
   `user-read-playback-state`
   `user-modify-playback-state`
   `user-read-currently-playing`
   `playlist-modify-public`
   `playlist-modify-private`
7. Copy the refresh token
8. Put the values in `.env`

```env
SPOTIFY_CLIENT_ID=your_client_id_here
SPOTIFY_CLIENT_SECRET=your_client_secret_here
SPOTIFY_REFRESH_TOKEN=your_refresh_token_here
```

### 3.9 Twilio WhatsApp

Needed for WhatsApp integration.

1. Go to `https://console.twilio.com/`
2. Create or sign in to your Twilio account
3. Copy your Account SID
4. Copy your Auth Token
5. Set up WhatsApp Sandbox or an approved WhatsApp sender
6. Put the values in `.env`

```env
TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID=your_account_sid_here
TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN=your_auth_token_here
TWILIO_WHATSAPP_FROM=whatsapp:+14155238886
```

If you are using the sandbox, the sender is usually the Twilio sandbox number.

### 3.10 Picovoice Porcupine

Needed only for wake-word voice mode.

1. Go to `https://console.picovoice.ai/`
2. Create an access key
3. Put it in `.env`

```env
PORCUPINE_ACCESS_KEY=your_access_key_here
```

### 3.11 Tavily

Needed if you want Tavily-backed web search.

1. Go to `https://tavily.com/`
2. Create an API key
3. Put it in `.env`

```env
TAVILY_API_KEY=your_key_here
```

### 3.12 Weather API

The codebase includes a weather integration that expects `WEATHER_API_KEY`.
This key is not listed in the main templates, but the integration exists.

1. Go to `https://openweathermap.org/api`
2. Create an API key
3. Add it to `.env`

```env
WEATHER_API_KEY=your_key_here
```

### 3.13 Email account credentials

Needed for the email integration.

These are mailbox credentials, not a separate API portal.

1. Use the email account you want Jarvis to access
2. Enable IMAP and SMTP for that provider
3. If your provider requires it, create an app password
4. Put the values in `.env`

```env
EMAIL_ADDRESS=you@example.com
EMAIL_PASSWORD=your_password_or_app_password
SMTP_HOST=smtp.gmail.com
SMTP_PORT=587
IMAP_HOST=imap.gmail.com
```

If you use Gmail, an app password is usually safer than your main password.

## Step 4: Turn cloud fallback on or off

If you want cloud fallback enabled:

```env
CLOUD_LLM_FALLBACK_ENABLED=true
```

If you want Jarvis to stay local-only when possible, keep using Ollama and only add cloud keys if needed.

## Step 5: Example `.env` starter block

Use this as a small starter checklist:

```env
JARVIS_DASHBOARD_TOKEN=replace_with_a_long_random_secret

# Recommended cloud fallback
GEMINI_API_KEY=

# Optional cloud providers
GROQ_API_KEY=
OPENAI_API_KEY=
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=

# Optional integrations
TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=
TELEGRAM_CHAT_ID=
GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=
GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=
GOOGLE_REFRESH_TOKEN=
NOTION_API_KEY=
SPOTIFY_CLIENT_ID=
SPOTIFY_CLIENT_SECRET=
SPOTIFY_REFRESH_TOKEN=
TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID=
TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN=
TWILIO_WHATSAPP_FROM=whatsapp:+14155238886
PORCUPINE_ACCESS_KEY=
TAVILY_API_KEY=
WEATHER_API_KEY=
EMAIL_ADDRESS=
EMAIL_PASSWORD=
SMTP_HOST=smtp.gmail.com
SMTP_PORT=587
IMAP_HOST=imap.gmail.com
```

## Step 6: Verify your setup

1. Make sure `.env` is saved in the project root
2. If using Ollama, run:

```powershell
ollama serve
ollama list
```

3. Start Jarvis
4. If an integration does not load, check:
   the env vars are filled in
   the optional Python package for that integration is installed

## Quick summary

Minimum practical setup:

1. Set `JARVIS_DASHBOARD_TOKEN`
2. Install and run Ollama
3. Optionally add `GEMINI_API_KEY`

Then add only the integration credentials you actually plan to use.
